{"questionId":"22505359","questionHtml":"<p>Consider the curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math> are non-zero constants.</p>\n<p>The curve has a local minimum point at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> and a vertical asymptote with equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognizes that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;(seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>passes through <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> so:</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;(seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>local minimum point at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> so:</p>\n<p>attempts to find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math> using quotient or product rule&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>substitutes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math> into the numerator of their <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>12</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> An incorrect numerator may lead to a correct equation.</p>\n<p>In this instance, award <em><strong>A0</strong> </em>here and do not award the final <em><strong>A</strong></em> mark.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>attempts to solve their <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;linear equations in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Three linear equations and a value for each of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math> need to be seen to gain the last <em><strong>M</strong></em> mark.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The last <em><strong>M</strong></em> mark is dependent on an equation formed from the numerator of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[8 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22505359","referenceCode":"24M.2.AHL.TZ2.9","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Consider the curve y=x-4ax2+bx+c, where a, b and c are non-zero constants. The curve has a local minimum point at 2, 1 and a vertical asymptote with equation x=1. Find the values o","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"9","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 8]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.13—Rational functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}